### CSS Pseudo-Elements

A **pseudo-element** styles a specific **part** of an element.

---

### Syntax (Double Colon)

```css
selector::pseudo-element {
  property: value;
}
```

CSS3 uses `::` (double colon) for pseudo-elements. Single `:` also works for backward compatibility.

---

### Pseudo-Elements List

| Pseudo-Element | Purpose |
|---------------|---------|
| `::first-letter` | First letter of text |
| `::first-line` | First line of text |
| `::before` | Content before element |
| `::after` | Content after element |
| `::selection` | Selected/highlighted text |
| `::marker` | List item marker |
| `::placeholder` | Input placeholder text |
| `::backdrop` | Full-screen element background |

---

### `::first-letter` and `::first-line`

```css
p::first-letter {
  font-size: 2em;
  color: red;
  font-weight: bold;
}

p::first-line {
  font-variant: small-caps;
}
```

---

### `::before` and `::after`

Insert content before/after an element:

```css
a::after {
  content: " \u2197";  /* Arrow icon */
}

.quote::before {
  content: "\201C";  /* Opening quote */
  font-size: 2em;
  color: gray;
}

.clearfix::after {
  content: "";
  display: table;
  clear: both;
}
```

---

### `::selection`

```css
::selection {
  background-color: yellow;
  color: black;
}
```

---

### `::placeholder`

```css
input::placeholder {
  color: gray;
  font-style: italic;
}
```

> **Key Point:** `::before` and `::after` require `content` property. They are inline by default.
